to:RuleAddition_FR_02 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:RuleAddition ;
    rdfs:label "FR Addition 2"@en ;
    to:additionNumber 2 ;
    to:appliedToLanguage to:French ;
    to:ruleText "IPA notation uses Le Petit Robert conventions including uvular r [ʀ] and French nasal vowels [ɛ̃], [ɑ̃], [ɔ̃], [œ̃]. When two IPA forms are given, both are standard."@en .

to:RuleAddition_FR_04 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:RuleAddition ;
    rdfs:label "FR Addition 4"@en ;
    to:additionNumber 4 ;
    to:appliedToLanguage to:French ;
    to:ruleText "UNRESOLVED: Silent letters in French orthography interact with Thai transliteration. Words written with final consonants that are phonetically absent require special handling."@en .

to:RuleAddition_FR_12 a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:RuleAddition ;
    rdfs:label "FR Addition 12"@en ;
    to:additionNumber 12 ;
    to:appliedToLanguage to:French ;
    to:ruleText "French alphabet. Each letter name has a fixed Thai rendering independent of its phonological context."@en .

<https://w3id.org/transonto/kg/all> a owl:Ontology ;
    dcterms:description "Merged knowledge graph for all three transliteration language KGs: German (180 entries, Rule_DE_01–31), French (92 entries, Add_FR_01–14), English (297 entries, Rule_EN_01–12). Total: 572 LexicalEntry, 564 BenchmarkItem, 13583 combined triples (with transonto.ttl)."@en ;
    dcterms:title "RoyalSocietyTransKG — All Languages"@en ;
    owl:imports <https://w3id.org/transonto/1.0>,
        <https://w3id.org/transonto/kg/de>,
        <https://w3id.org/transonto/kg/en>,
        <https://w3id.org/transonto/kg/fr> ;
    owl:versionInfo "1.0" .

to:Decision_DE_17_Rad a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:ExpertDecision ;
    rdfs:label "Decision DE 17 Rad"@en ;
    to:decisionJustification "For Rad and similar VC̄ words where r can be [ʁ], [r], or [ʀ]: use รัท as default; regional variants may use รา."@en ;
    to:madeByExpert to:Expert_RoyalSociety_DE .

to:Decision_DE_21_final_r a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:ExpertDecision ;
    rdfs:label "Decision DE 21 final r"@en ;
    to:decisionJustification "Final coda r after a short vowel: retain as ร์ in Thai. Karl→คาร์ล. r is not dropped but its syllabic value depends on stress."@en ;
    to:madeByExpert to:Expert_RoyalSociety_DE .

to:Decision_DE_25_loanword a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:ExpertDecision ;
    rdfs:label "Decision DE 25 loanword"@en ;
    to:decisionJustification "French loanwords in German that retain French phonology are identified by ʒ, ɲ in IPA. Genie, Blammage confirmed as French-phonology items."@en ;
    to:madeByExpert to:Expert_RoyalSociety_DE .

to:Decision_DE_27_von a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:ExpertDecision ;
    rdfs:label "Decision DE 27 von"@en ;
    to:decisionJustification "von→ฟอน (standard); zu→ซู (standard). No context-dependent variation; committee uses these forms consistently."@en ;
    to:madeByExpert to:Expert_RoyalSociety_DE .

to:Decision_EN_01_k a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:ExpertDecision ;
    rdfs:label "Decision EN 01 k"@en ;
    to:decisionJustification "For /k/ initial: rule-based system uses ค, but established conventional words use ก (copy→ก๊อบปี้, karat→กะรัต). System must use lexicon lookup for conventional forms; rule alone is insufficient."@en ;
    to:madeByExpert to:Expert_NECTEC_EN .

to:Decision_EN_05_silent a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:ExpertDecision ;
    rdfs:label "Decision EN 05 silent"@en ;
    to:decisionJustification "Silent consonants are retained in conventional Thai transliteration to preserve English source spelling. bomb→บอมบ์, walk→วอล์ก, column→คอลัมน์. IPA-based systems cannot reproduce these without a pronunciation-to-spelling reverse lookup."@en ;
    to:madeByExpert to:Expert_NECTEC_EN .

to:Decision_EN_09_diphthong a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:ExpertDecision ;
    rdfs:label "Decision EN 09 diphthong"@en ;
    to:decisionJustification "/aɪ/ renders as สระไอ when no following consonant (spy→สปาย) or before certain consonants (style→สไตล์). Both patterns are valid; conventional usage takes precedence over pure phoneme mapping."@en ;
    to:madeByExpert to:Expert_NECTEC_EN .

to:Decision_EN_11_maitaikhu a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:ExpertDecision ;
    rdfs:label "Decision EN 11 maitaikhu"@en ;
    to:decisionJustification "ไม้ไต่คู้ is used when Thai transliteration might be confused with existing Thai words or when context demands disambiguation (lock→ล็อก, impact→อิมแพ็กต์). Rule-based systems lack this contextual knowledge."@en ;
    to:madeByExpert to:Expert_NECTEC_EN .

to:Decision_FR_03_nasal a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:ExpertDecision ;
    rdfs:label "Decision FR 03 nasal"@en ;
    to:decisionJustification "Nasal vowel [ɑ̃]/[ɔ̃] renders as อ็อง in open syllable. [ɛ̃]/[œ̃] renders as แ_ง. Proper noun nasals follow standard phonological mapping. champagne→ชองปาน confirmed by committee."@en ;
    to:madeByExpert to:Expert_RoyalSociety_FR .

to:Decision_FR_09_yod a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:ExpertDecision ;
    rdfs:label "Decision FR 09 yod"@en ;
    to:decisionJustification "Yod [j] from -ille, -ill- renders as ย. When schwa deletion produces consonant cluster, preceding consonant is attached to the previous syllable in Thai rendering."@en ;
    to:madeByExpert to:Expert_RoyalSociety_FR .

to:Decision_FR_13_h a owl:NamedIndividual,
        to:ExpertDecision ;
    rdfs:label "Decision FR 13 h"@en ;
    to:decisionJustification "H aspiré blocks liaison: le haricot→เลอ อาริโก (no linking). H muet allows liaison: les hommes→เลซอม. Committee relies on Le Petit Robert diacritic [ʼ] notation to mark h aspiré."@en ;
    to:madeByExpert to:Expert_RoyalSociety_FR .

